[2026-04-26 21:43:58,602] [-] [INFO] [BaseAgent]: Agent 'agent5' acted with result 'Message(content="Let's proceed with refining the methodology section based on the research idea you've outlined. Here’s a detailed breakdown of the methodology, including specific datasets, models, and evaluation metrics:\n\n### Methodology\n\n#### Datasets\n1. **Alzheimer's Disease (AD) Dataset:**\n   - **Type:** EEG data\n   - **Source:** Publicly available EEG datasets such as the Alzheimer's Disease Neuroimaging Initiative (ADNI) or the International EEG Database.\n   - **Description:** The dataset will include EEG recordings from both AD patients and healthy controls. Specific EEG frequency bands (e.g., delta, theta, alpha, beta, gamma) will be analyzed using complexity measures like Tsallis entropy, Higuchi Fractal Dimension, and Lempel-Ziv complexity.\n\n2. **Autism Spectrum Disorder (ASD) Dataset:**\n   - **Type:** Resting-state functional MRI (fMRI) data\n   - **Source:** Autism Brain Imaging Data Exchange (ABIDE)\n   - **Description:** The dataset will consist of resting-state fMRI scans from individuals with ASD and typical controls. The data will be preprocessed to ensure consistency and quality.\n\n#### Models\n1. **Deep Learning Models for AD:**\n   - **Type:** Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) and Recurrent Neural Networks (RNNs)\n   - **Description:** These models will be trained to classify EEG data into AD and non-AD categories. The models will incorporate complexity measures as input features to improve diagnostic accuracy.\n\n2. **Deep Learning Models for ASD:**\n   - **Type:** Graph Neural Networks (GNNs)\n   - **Description:** GNNs will be used to analyze the connectivity patterns in fMRI data. The models will be designed to classify ASD and non-ASD cases while providing interpretable insights into critical brain regions.\n\n#### Evaluation Metrics\n1. **For AD:**\n   - **Sensitivity:** The proportion of true positive cases (AD patients correctly identified) out of the actual positive cases.\n   - **Specificity:** The proportion of true negative cases (healthy individuals correctly identified) out of the actual negative cases.\n   - **Accuracy:** The overall proportion of correct predictions (both true positives and true negatives) out of the total number of cases.\n   - **Area Under the Receiver Operating Characteristic Curve (AUC-ROC):** A measure of the model's ability to distinguish between AD and non-AD cases.\n\n2. **For ASD:**\n   - **Classification Accuracy:** The proportion of correctly classified cases (both ASD and non-ASD) out of the total number of cases.\n   - **Interpretability Score:** A custom metric to evaluate the clarity and relevance of the model's explanations. This could involve human evaluation of the explanations or automated measures of coherence and alignment with clinical understanding.\n\n#### Challenges and Solutions\n1. **Challenge:** Handling high-dimensional and complex data.\n   - **Solution:** Use advanced preprocessing techniques and dimensionality reduction methods to simplify the data while retaining important features.\n\n2. **Challenge:** Ensuring model interpretability.\n   - **Solution:** Incorporate attention mechanisms and other interpretability techniques into the models to highlight key features and decision-making processes.\n\n3. **Challenge:** Validating the models on diverse datasets.\n   - **Solution:** Use multiple datasets from different sources to ensure the models generalize well to various populations and conditions.\n\n### Expected Outcomes\n1. **Improved Diagnostic Tools:**\n   - Develop deep learning models that achieve high sensitivity and specificity in diagnosing AD and ASD.\n   - Provide interpretable insights into the decision-making processes of the models, enhancing clinical trust and understanding.\n\n2. **Advancements in Explainable AI:**\n   - Contribute to the field of explainable AI by developing methods that generate contextual explanations for deep