ops where users can provide feedback on explanations, helping to refine and improve the model's interpretability.\n\n### Summarization\n\nThe main challenge in deep learning models is their lack of explainability, particularly in safety-critical applications. Current local explanation methods, such as saliency maps, are often misleading and counter-intuitive. To address these issues, we can develop contextual saliency maps, integrate rule-based systems, create hybrid models, use attention mechanisms, and implement user feedback loops.\n\n### Formulate a New Research Idea\n\n**[Question 1] - What is the problem?**\nHow can we develop explainable deep learning models for safety-critical applications that provide accurate and contextually relevant explanations?\n\n**[Question 2] - Why is it interesting and important?**\nSolving this problem is crucial for building trust in autonomous systems and ensuring their safe and reliable operation. Accurate explanations can help identify and mitigate biases, improve model robustness, and facilitate better decision-making in critical scenarios.\n\n**[Question 3] - Why is it hard?**\nCreating explainable models is challenging due to the complex and non-linear nature of deep learning architectures. Traditional attribution-based methods often fail to capture the broader context and can produce misleading explanations. Additionally, integrating interpretability into existing models without sacrificing performance is a significant technical challenge.\n\n**[Question 4] - Why hasn't it been solved before?**\nPrevious approaches have focused on local explanations that are often contextually irrelevant and misleading. There is a need for more sophisticated methods that can incorporate contextual information and provide accurate, interpretable explanations. Additionally, the integration of interpretability into deep learning models has been hindered by the trade-off between performance and explainability.\n\n**[Question 5] - What are the 